Yes, it is recommended to indicate the foreign key relationships in your code. This helps define the relationships between the tables and allows Entity Framework to understand and enforce the relationships at the database level.

In the models you provided, the `Enrollment` table has `UserID` and `CourseID` columns that serve as foreign keys referencing the `Users` and `Courses` tables respectively. To indicate these relationships in your code, you can use data annotations or the Fluent API.

Using data annotations, you can specify the `[ForeignKey]` attribute on the foreign key properties:

```csharp
public class Enrollment
{
    public int EnrollmentID { get; set; }

    [ForeignKey("User")]
    public int UserID { get; set; }

    [ForeignKey("Course")]
    public int CourseID { get; set; }

    public DateTime EnrollmentDate { get; set; }

    public User User { get; set; }
    public Course Course { get; set; }
}
```

Alternatively, you can use the Fluent API to configure the relationships in the `OnModelCreating` method of your `DbContext` class:

```csharp
protected override void OnModelCreating(DbModelBuilder modelBuilder)
{
    modelBuilder.Entity<Enrollment>()
                .HasRequired(e => e.User)
                .WithMany(u => u.Enrollments)
                .HasForeignKey(e => e.UserID);

    modelBuilder.Entity<Enrollment>()
                .HasRequired(e => e.Course)
                .WithMany(c => c.Enrollments)
                .HasForeignKey(e => e.CourseID);
}
```

By specifying the foreign key relationships, you ensure that the associations between the tables are properly defined, and Entity Framework can generate the appropriate database schema.

Note that the examples provided assume a one-to-many relationship between `User` and `Enrollment`, and between `Course` and `Enrollment`. If you have different relationship types, you will need to adjust the code accordingly.

